{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783744267628,"sessionID":"ses_0b0929e3affe1FHkKX9E1sdw9Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_ubAK2fNWu1jnjdfyaPlkJAy3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"hook|plugin|enforce|guard|validate|inject|route|dispatch|preflight|postflight","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills","include":"SKILL.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-git/SKILL.md:\n  Line 33: **Owned (route here):** `git worktree`, `worktree`, `create worktree`, `numbered worktree`, `restructure worktrees`, `worktree prefix`, `wt/ branch`, `branch`, `commit`, `conventional commits`, `pull request`, `pr`, `pr review`, `merge`, `rebase`, `finish work`, `integrate changes`, `git workflow`, `github`, `issue`, `gitkraken`, `gitlens`, `gitlens launchpad`, `commit composer`\n\n  Line 104: def _guard_in_skill(relative_path: str) -> str:\n\n  Line 119:     \"\"\"Boundary-aware match: bare substrings misroute ('pr' in 'improve prompt').\"\"\"\n\n  Line 160: def route_git_resources(task):\n\n  Line 169:         guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)\n\n  Line 170:         if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:\n\n  Line 171:             load(guarded)\n\n  Line 172:             loaded.append(guarded)\n\n  Line 173:             seen.add(guarded)\n\n  Line 227: **Deliberate per-session deps override.** The wrapper **symlinks** the shared `node_modules`/`dist` from the main checkout into each worktree and gives each worktree its own MCP DBs (via `SPEC_KIT_DB_DIR` / `SPECKIT_CODE_GRAPH_DB_DIR` / `SPECKIT_IPC_SOCKET_DIR`). This is an intentional exception to the §4 \"bare worktree lacks gitignored deps / DBs are a single global instance\" guidance: that guidance is about *ad-hoc* worktrees for large reorgs, whereas the wrapper purpose-builds an isolated-but-runnable worktree. Strict-validate and memory reindex still run on `main`, never inside a wrapper worktree.\n\n  Line 302: 8. **Defer toolchain + DB work to main on large reorgs** - For large rename/reorg, do file/`git mv` ops in the worktree but run the spec-kit toolchain (strict validate, generators, metadata regen) and ALL memory reindex/re-embed on `main` AFTER merge. A bare worktree lacks gitignored deps (`node_modules`/`dist`) and the memory/vector DBs are a single global instance — never per-worktree. See [large_reorg_playbook.md](references/large_reorg_playbook.md).\n\n  Line 314: Enforced structurally (not clarity semantics) by the `commit-msg` hook — see\n\n  Line 315: [git-hooks/commit-msg](../../scripts/git-hooks/commit-msg); bypass with\n\n  Line 316: `SPECKIT_SKIP_COMMIT_MSG_VALIDATE=1 git commit ...` only when the hook is\n\n  Line 386: 2. `.opencode/scripts/git-hooks/...` or its installer -> `git-hooks`.\n\n  Line 404: 2. Start with the action: `add`, `prevent`, `preserve`, `route`, `remove`,\n\n  Line 479: 8. **Strict-validate run inside a bare worktree** - Its exit code is meaningless (missing gitignored deps may make it silently no-op on zero files). Re-run on `main` post-merge before trusting any result. See [large_reorg_playbook.md](references/large_reorg_playbook.md).\n\n  Line 577: The router discovers reference, asset, and script docs dynamically. Start with `references/quick_reference.md`, `references/worktree_workflows.md`, `references/commit_workflows.md`, `references/finish_workflows.md`, `references/github_mcp_integration.md`, `references/shared_patterns.md`, `assets/commit_message_template.md`, then load task-specific resources from `references/`, templates from `assets/`, and automation from `scripts/` when present.\n\n  Line 581: Manual testing scenarios for this skill live in `manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md` (root index) plus 22 per-feature sub-files under `manual_testing_playbook/<NN>--<topic>/<NNN>-<scenario>.md`. Run scenarios via `bash .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/validate_document.py manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md` for structural validation; execute scenarios in opencode/Claude/OpenCode sessions for behavioral verification.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-quality-control/SKILL.md:\n  Line 29: Keyword triggers: `doc quality`, `/doc:quality`, `DQI`, `document audit`, `validate markdown`, `score this document`, `optimize this doc`, `HVR`, `human voice`, `AI-friendly documentation`, `extract structure`.\n\n  Line 77: `extract_structure.py` takes only the file path. It always prints its full analysis as JSON to stdout and auto-detects the document type from path and content, so there are no flags to pass here. The `--json` and `--type readme|skill|reference|asset|agent|command|install_guide|spec|changelog` options belong to `validate_document.py` (the validation step below), not the extractor.\n\n  Line 101: python ../shared/scripts/validate_document.py <file>\n\n  Line 107: python ../shared/scripts/quick_validate.py <path>\n\n  Line 244: python ../shared/scripts/validate_document.py <file>\n\n  Line 250: python ../shared/scripts/quick_validate.py <path>\n\n  Line 317: 6. Validate edited documents with `../shared/scripts/validate_document.py` when applicable.\n\n  Line 366: Use these only for deep overflow detail, edge cases, exhaustive templates and long examples. Start at the route map, then open the single-concern file the task needs:\n\n  Line 369: - `references/validation_and_enforcement.md` - Validation touchpoints, enforcement approval-prompt templates, phase interactions and troubleshooting.\n\n  Line 374: - `../shared/scripts/validate_document.py` - Pre-delivery document validation gate.\n\n  Line 375: - `../shared/scripts/quick_validate.py` - Fast validation for folders or skill packets.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-manual-testing-playbook/SKILL.md:\n  Line 260: python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/validate_document.py <SKILL_PATH>/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md --type reference\n\n  Line 266: - Broken local links, by grep/script or the repository markdown-link guard.\n\n  Line 273: The current validator is root-document focused. It does not recurse into category folders and does not prove every cross-file playbook link by itself. Cross-file markdown links are covered separately by the `check-markdown-links.cjs` CI guard, which verifies every markdown link across skills, commands, and agents and fails the PR on a broken link; per-feature file structure inside the category folders still needs manual review.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-benchmark/SKILL.md:\n  Line 112: Reference `references/README.md` for deep overflow: it routes to the case studies, the report worked example, and common pitfalls.\n\n  Line 129: 10. **Validate authored markdown.** Run `python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/validate_document.py --type readme <file>` on `benchmark_report.md` and `benchmarks/README.md`. Fix blocking issues before delivery.\n\n  Line 161: 8. **RECOMMENDATIONS**: Tier 1 apply now, Tier 2 validate first, Tier 3 future.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/SKILL.md:\n  Line 109: - `references/README.md` to route the reference overflow — [`examples.md`](references/examples.md) (worked live-catalog walkthrough) and [`common_pitfalls.md`](references/common_pitfalls.md) (deep-dive pitfalls, template-versus-reference split) — only for depth beyond this inline workflow.\n\n  Line 224: | Manual testing playbook | How do we validate that behavior manually? |\n\n  Line 236: python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/validate_document.py <target-skill>/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md\n\n  Line 239: # Each per-feature leaf (detected as the feature_catalog doc type; validates the Validation And Tests table taxonomy)\n\n  Line 240: python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/validate_document.py <target-skill>/feature_catalog/NN--category/feature-name.md\n\n  Line 255: - `validate_document.py` checks root-catalog structure and, for per-feature leaves reached by a repo-root path, the Validation And Tests table taxonomy.\n\n  Line 256: - Cross-file link resolution is enforced in CI by `check-markdown-links.cjs`.\n\n  Line 299: 5. Validation fails in `../shared/scripts/validate_document.py` and the safe fix is not obvious.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/SKILL.md:\n  Line 3: description: Scaffold OpenCode slash commands with explicit argument hints, allowed tools, and router/presentation separation.\n\n  Line 8: <!-- Keywords: create-command, slash command, opencode command, argument-hint, allowed-tools, command router, presentation contract, thin router, command scaffold -->\n\n  Line 12: `create-command` is the command-authoring workflow packet of the `sk-doc` parent hub. It creates and improves OpenCode slash commands under `.opencode/commands/` with executable workflows, precise frontmatter, required input gates, least-privilege tools, and router/presentation separation when needed.\n\n  Line 14: This SKILL.md contains the core creation workflow. Use the `references/` route map (`references/README.md`), `assets/command_template.md`, `assets/command_router_template.md`, `assets/command_presentation_template.md`, and `../shared/` only for exhaustive examples, edge cases, and validator implementation detail.\n\n  Line 25: - Refactoring a command into a thin router plus owned presentation asset.\n\n  Line 32: Keyword triggers: `create command`, `slash command`, `opencode command`, `argument-hint`, `allowed-tools`, `command template`, `router presentation split`, `thin router`, `presentation contract`, `$ARGUMENTS`, `:auto`, `:confirm`.\n\n  Line 96: | Mode-based | Supports `:auto` / `:confirm` | Thin router plus owned assets when complex |\n\n  Line 97: | Router | Thin dispatcher: verify agent, resolve mode/args, hand off to owned assets | Router `.md` plus owned presentation `.txt` and optional workflow YAML or scripts |\n\n  Line 98: | Argument dispatch | Multiple action keywords or query forms | ASCII routing tree plus handlers |\n\n  Line 102: If the command combines patterns, parse mode first, then dispatch remaining arguments.\n\n  Line 127: Use `_auto.yaml` and `_confirm.yaml` only for workflow-backed families that route execution into workflow assets. Direct-router families dispatch directly to tools/scripts and do not need workflow YAML.\n\n  Line 129: For a compiled-stub router, the `.md` is a generated thin stub carrying the `render-command-contract` marker; its section shape is rendered from a compiled source at invocation, not authored in the file. Do not hand-write section headings into a compiled stub, and keep its owned presentation/workflow assets alongside it:\n\n  Line 228: Approved canonical H2 section names for router commands (see Step 11):\n\n  Line 261: Autonomous mode self-validates at checkpoints, makes informed decisions, and records significant decisions.\n\n  Line 265: If the mode-based command is large or has visible dashboards/prompts/results, use the router/presentation split.\n\n  Line 269: A router is a first-class command type, not a loose refactor. Its `.md` is a thin dispatcher: verify the orchestrating agent, resolve mode and arguments, then hand off to owned assets (a presentation `.txt`, optional `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml`, or scripts). It carries no inline dashboards, prompts, or result templates.\n\n  Line 271: **Detection signature.** The validator treats a command as a router when any of:\n\n  Line 277: **Minimal core vs recommended.** A router must include the blocking core only: `Owned Assets` and `Presentation Boundary`. The remaining canonical sections — `Router Contract`, `Mode Routing`, `Execution Targets`, `Workflow Summary` — are recommended and surface as non-blocking warnings when absent. Author the full shape for new routers; the minimal core lets incremental migrations land without failing.\n\n  Line 279: **Canonical vocabulary (numbered `## N.`, full integers).** Use exactly these H2 names, in this order, for a fully-shaped router:\n\n  Line 292: **Ownership boundary.** The router owns: the mandatory input gate or Phase 0, the owned-assets table, mode resolution, argument routing, execution-target selection, the presentation boundary, and a short workflow summary. The presentation asset owns: startup prompts and consolidated setup questions, auto fail-fast display text, dashboard and checkpoint layouts, success and failure result templates, and next-step suggestions. The router must not contain inline startup-question wording, dashboard templates, result templates, or next-step wording when a presentation asset exists. The split is behavior-preserving: move display content, do not change routing semantics.\n\n  Line 296: - Workflow-YAML-backed — routes execution into `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml` workflow assets (for example the deep-large and speckit families).\n\n  Line 297: - Direct-dispatch-script — dispatches directly to tools or scripts, no workflow YAML (for example the skill-benchmark, doctor, and memory families).\n\n  Line 300: Use `assets/command_router_template.md` for the canonical numbered router skeleton, and `assets/command_presentation_template.md` for the full presentation asset skeleton.\n\n  Line 332: - Thin routers contain no presentation templates when a presentation asset exists.\n\n  Line 333: - Router commands carry the blocking core (`OWNED ASSETS` + `PRESENTATION BOUNDARY`) and use the canonical numbered vocabulary from Step 11; remaining router sections are present or intentionally left as warnings.\n\n  Line 338: python3 ../shared/scripts/validate_document.py <command-file.md> --type command\n\n  Line 342: Exit code `0` from `validate_document.py` is required before stating that the command document is structurally valid. If validation cannot be run, say that explicitly.\n\n  Line 368: 5. Never put dashboards, startup prompts, or result templates inside a thin router when a presentation asset exists.\n\n  Line 389: - `references/README.md` - overflow route map for this packet; indexes the single-concern reference files below.\n\n  Line 390: - `references/worked_example.md` - the canonical file contract plus a fully worked split command (router `.md` and presentation `.txt`).\n\n  Line 391: - `references/router_presentation_split.md` - router/presentation ownership, the before/after split transformation, and the behavior-preserving rule.\n\n  Line 395: - `assets/command_router_template.md` - canonical numbered router skeleton with variant call-outs.\n\n  Line 399: - `../shared/scripts/validate_document.py` - blocking structure validation.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external/SKILL.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Parent hub for external CLI dispatch: routes to two workflow modes (cli-opencode, cli-claude-code) through mode-registry.json. Holds no per-mode logic; dispatches by workflowMode.\"\n\n  Line 11: <!-- Keywords: cli-external, mode-registry, hub-router, workflowMode, packetKind, cli-opencode, opencode-cli, opencode-run, cli-claude-code, claude-code, claude-cli, cross-ai, agent-delegation, executor-delegation -->\n\n  Line 15: One skill, two workflow modes, one shared `family: cli` identity. `cli-external` is the public, advisor-routable home for every external CLI dispatch orchestrator in this repo. Before routing, the hub reads `hub-router.json` to resolve a `workflowMode`, then delegates through `mode-registry.json`. This hub holds NO per-mode logic — each mode keeps its own dispatch contract, self-invocation guard, and hard rules in its packet, and the hub only routes by `workflowMode`.\n\n  Line 21: Use this skill (through the hub) for any cross-AI CLI dispatch. Invoke it as `cli-external`; the hub classifies the request, resolves a mode key, and loads the matching nested packet.\n\n  Line 25: | **cli-opencode** | workflow | OpenCode CLI orchestration: external dispatch, in-OpenCode parallel/detached sessions, full plugin/skill/MCP/Spec-Kit-Memory runtime, small-model dispatch (DeepSeek, Kimi, MiniMax, MiMo, GLM) | `cli-external/cli-opencode/` |\n\n  Line 30: - The current runtime IS the target CLI — each mode's own self-invocation guard refuses self-dispatch (see that packet's §2); this hub does no dispatch itself and carries no guard of its own.\n\n  Line 31: - Application-code implementation, review, or design work with no CLI-dispatch need — use `sk-code` / `sk-design` directly.\n\n  Line 32: - A quick in-process task with no cross-AI handoff — dispatching to an external CLI process is unnecessary overhead.\n\n  Line 38: Routing is registry-driven. `mode-registry.json` lists both modes in one `modes[]` array. `hub-router.json` decides whether the result is a single mode, an ordered bundle, or a deferred disambiguation.\n\n  Line 42: - `packetKind: \"workflow\"` — both `cli-opencode` and `cli-claude-code` orchestrate a CLI binary and their dispatched writes land in THIS repo's workspace (`mutatesWorkspace:true`). Neither is a transport packet: both classify intent, choose/confirm a provider, and conduct the dispatched session — the transport contract requires a non-orchestrating packet whose writes land externally, and neither packet qualifies (ADR-001).\n\n  Line 43: - Zero extensions: no surface-axis, no transport-axis, no runtime-loop. Both modes are primary, independently-routable dispatch workflows.\n\n  Line 48: read hub-router.json\n\n  Line 49:   -> score routerSignals and vocabularyClasses\n\n  Line 50:   -> apply routerPolicy.tieBreak\n\n  Line 57: - `single`: one dominant executor signal routes to one mode.\n\n  Line 58: - `orderedBundle`: multiple explicitly requested executors route in tie-break order.\n\n  Line 59: - `defer`: unclear or contradictory dispatch intent asks for disambiguation — the router does not silently default to `cli-opencode` on genuine ambiguity.\n\n  Line 63: A prompt naming a specific executor (e.g. \"use cli-opencode\", \"delegate to opencode\", \"get a claude code second opinion\", or a small model that dispatches through one) is resolved by the system-skill-advisor's executor-delegation scorer, which sources its alias table from THIS hub's `mode-registry.json` — keyed by each mode's `packetSkillName` — and resolves to the executor-kind strings `cli-opencode` / `cli-claude-code`. See `system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/executor-delegation.ts`.\n\n  Line 75:   hub-router.json\n\n  Line 101: - `hub-router.json` owns `routerPolicy`, `routerSignals`, `vocabularyClasses`.\n\n  Line 107: Each mode's self-invocation guard is runtime-signal-based (env var / process ancestry / lockfile), not path-based, so it is unaffected by this hub's routing layer. `cli-opencode` additionally carries a parallel-detached carve-out that `cli-claude-code` intentionally does not — that asymmetry is preserved.\n\n  Line 119: - Keep `hub-router.json` signal keys and registry `workflowMode` values bidirectionally aligned.\n\n  Line 120: - Read the target mode's `SKILL.md` before composing any dispatch prompt (constitutional cli-dispatch-skill-preload rule) — the advisor recommendation alone does not waive this.\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"hook|plugin|enforce|guard|validate|inject|route|dispatch|preflight|postflight","time":{"start":1783744267466,"end":1783744267606}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0eb284b406afc4ec016a51c70b3cb88191a322ba6b5d88822a"}},"id":"prt_f4f7184c8001T4vUu5V37RWfnn","sessionID":"ses_0b0929e3affe1FHkKX9E1sdw9Y","messageID":"msg_f4f712ed9001qIozfBqc1jfE3e"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783744267683,"sessionID":"ses_0b0929e3affe1FHkKX9E1sdw9Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_DruJZFZjVMe2dFdWbJWLWtPZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"tool\\.execute\\.(before|after)|session\\.|experimental\\.|PreToolUse|PostToolUse|SessionStart|UserPromptSubmit|SessionEnd|\\bStop\\b","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode","include":"*.{ts,js,mjs,cjs,json,jsonc,md}"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/install_guides/MCP - Sequential Thinking.md:\n  Line 439: **Typical usage:** approximately 1,500 to 2,500 tokens per thinking session.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/install_guides/SET-UP - AGENTS.md:\n  Line 815: ❌ **STOP if validation fails** - Fix any mismatches between AGENTS.md references and your actual environment before testing with a live AI session.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-git/SKILL.md:\n  Line 225: The ask-first rule above governs **in-session** decisions: once an AI is running, it must not autonomously create a worktree. That is distinct from `.opencode/bin/worktree-session.sh`, a **launch wrapper** the operator opts into at the shell (e.g. `alias claude='bash /abs/.opencode/bin/worktree-session.sh claude'`). The wrapper runs *before* the AI starts and places each top-level session in its own worktree + branch + isolated MCP databases automatically; orchestrated children (`AI_SESSION_CHILD=1`, or already inside a linked worktree) exec in place. Because the wrapper acts pre-session at operator opt-in, it does not violate the in-session ask-first rule — the operator made the choice by aliasing the launch.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:\n  Line 587: | Context budget exceeded      | Stop dispatching, synthesize current results, report to user (§8)                                |\n\n  Line 588: | Context pressure detected    | Stop new dispatches → synthesize completed results → suggest file-based collection for remainder |\n\n  Line 651: | **Context pressure** | **Any warning** | **Stop dispatching, synthesize current results**   |\n\n  Line 711: | Step 9 (SYNTHESIZE) | Context approaching 80%?              | Stop collecting, synthesize what we have  |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-git/references/worktree_workflows.md:\n  Line 156: > worktrees allocated by the launch wrapper `.opencode/bin/worktree-session.sh`, which\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/code.md:\n  Line 171: | **REJECTED** | 0-49 | FAIL | Stop and return `BLOCKED`; implementation is unsafe, off-scope, unverified, or structurally mismatched |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-git/README.md:\n  Line 86: The skill never decides your branch strategy on its own. Every session that starts new work asks you to choose an isolated worktree or the current branch, and it holds that choice for the rest of the session. New branches are created one way only, through `git worktree add -b ...`. The direct commands `git branch`, `git checkout -b` and `git switch -c` are off the table, so a branch never exists without a worktree set up for it.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/deep-research.md:\n  Line 38: **HARD BLOCK INVARIANTS**: Stop before research or writes if any invariant fails.\n\n  Line 545: | Exceed tool budget | May timeout or get cut off mid-research | Stop research at budget limit, write and verify what you have |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/commands/deep/assets/compiled/deep_ai-council.contract.md:\n  Line 234: 1. **Tier 1 - Resolve confidently**: parse `$ARGUMENTS` flags, the `PRE-BOUND SETUP ANSWERS:` block, and the Default Resolution Table below. When every required field is resolved, persist to `{spec_folder}/ai-council/council-session.json` or the YAML-designated setup artifact, bind runtime YAML placeholders, set `STATUS: PASSED`, and load `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_ai-council_auto.yaml`. End Section 0.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/deep-improvement.md:\n  Line 198: ### Stop-Reason Awareness\n\n  Line 246: │  └─► 5. Stop                                                            │\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/commands/deep/assets/compiled/deep_review.contract.md:\n  Line 233: **Stop policy:** `stop_policy=convergence` preserves normal deep-review behavior: legal convergence may stop before `maxIterations`. `stop_policy=max-iterations` makes convergence signals telemetry-only until the iteration ceiling; before `maxIterations`, broaden the next angle instead of synthesizing. Terminal manual pause, user stop, unrecoverable error, and `maxIterationsReached` still stop.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/.goal-state/.archive/7365735f30646365633761663366666573334967796f65523932475a5246.json:\n  Line 5:   \"goalPrompt\": \"Role: Focused OpenCode execution agent operating under the active session goal.\\nObjective: Fix finding 0003 in the pre-approved spec folder by minimally correcting BM25 re-index gate trigger-mutation detection, editing only mcp_server TypeScript paths and avoiding banned git/database operations.\\nContext: Use the current conversation, repository files, tests, and active spec constraints as source of truth. Preserve unrelated worktree changes and do not broaden scope.\\nMethod:\\n- Restate the concrete completion condition from available evidence before acting.\\n- Find the root cause before changing code; verify the fix against the failing symptom.\\n- Prefer direct, reversible changes; ask only when blocked by missing information, permissions, or contradictory requirements.\\nSuccess Criteria:\\n- The requested outcome is materially complete, not merely analyzed or partially prepared.\\n- Required verification has run, or any inability to run it is reported with the exact blocker.\\n- Status output distinguishes confirmed evidence from inference.\\nStop Conditions:\\n- Stop only when the goal verifier can mark the goal met, when the user changes or clears the goal, or when progress is blocked by a decision the user must make.\\n- If blocked, preserve state and name the next safe action.\",\n\n  Line 19:         \"Stop Conditions\"\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/.goal-state/.archive/736d6f6b652d73657373696f6e2d31373832383939303735373237.json:\n  Line 5:   \"goalPrompt\": \"Role: Focused OpenCode execution agent operating under the active session goal.\\nObjective: Smoke test.\\nContext: Use the current conversation, repository files, tests, and active spec constraints as source of truth. Preserve unrelated worktree changes and do not broaden scope.\\nMethod:\\n- Restate the concrete completion condition from available evidence before acting.\\n- Run the relevant verification commands and report exact pass/fail evidence.\\n- Prefer direct, reversible changes; ask only when blocked by missing information, permissions, or contradictory requirements.\\nSuccess Criteria:\\n- The requested outcome is materially complete, not merely analyzed or partially prepared.\\n- Required verification has run, or any inability to run it is reported with the exact blocker.\\n- Status output distinguishes confirmed evidence from inference.\\nStop Conditions:\\n- Stop only when the goal verifier can mark the goal met, when the user changes or clears the goal, or when progress is blocked by a d