 and their downstream helpers) live under `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/hooks/`, NOT under `.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/hooks/`. This is an intentional asymmetry vs the `system-skill-advisor` pattern where hooks are skill-owned (ADR-001 for skill-advisor).\n\n  Line 87: When editing SessionStart-related code that needs to read or write code-graph state, look in `system-spec-kit/mcp_server/hooks/` and `system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/code-graph-boundary.ts`, not `system-code-graph/mcp_server/`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/133-plugin-hook-opportunities/spec.md:\n  Line 38: The repo ships seven OpenCode plugins with paired Claude hooks, but a much larger body of skills (`sk-code`, `sk-design`, `sk-doc`, `sk-git`, `sk-prompt`, `system-deep-loop`, `system-spec-kit`, `system-skill-advisor`, `system-code-graph`, cli-external hubs, mcp-tooling hubs) exposes capability that is only reachable interactively. Some of that capability would be more valuable surfaced as an always-on plugin (OpenCode `tool.execute.*` / session lifecycle) or Claude hook (PreToolUse / SessionStart / UserPromptSubmit / Stop), the way the current seven already are.\n\n  Line 81: | REQ-002 | Every candidate names a concrete runtime surface | Candidate specifies plugin hook (tool.execute.*/session.*) or Claude hook (PreToolUse/SessionStart/etc.) |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/references/config/database_path_policy.md:\n  Line 119: Cross-skill consumers reach the data through two paths: in-process imports from `system-spec-kit` handlers and hooks, and the warm daemon — which serves both the standalone MCP namespace used by agents and commands and the additive daemon-backed `code-index` CLI shim used as a warm-only fallback by the OpenCode plugin bridge. SessionStart hooks remain under `system-spec-kit/mcp_server/hooks/` due to 110-plus file references. This asymmetry is intentional and any future move is planned as a separate packet with build and config redesign scope.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/133-plugin-hook-opportunities/research/lineages/gptsol/deep-research-strategy.md:\n  Line 12: - [ ] Which additional Claude hooks are justified, and which exact `PreToolUse`, `PostToolUse`, `SessionStart`, `UserPromptSubmit`, `Stop`, or `SessionEnd` surfaces should host them?\n\n  Line 96: - The requested runtime surface set is closed: OpenCode `tool.execute.before/after`, `session.*`, `experimental.*`; Claude `PreToolUse`, `PostToolUse`, `SessionStart`, `UserPromptSubmit`, `Stop`, `SessionEnd`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/ARCHITECTURE.md:\n  Line 146: The code-graph does not own its own SessionStart hook surface. The hook runtime lives in a sibling spec-kit package and reaches code-graph data through a stable boundary import. This asymmetry vs the advisor pattern is intentional and documented as ADR-001 below. Plugin bridges under `plugin_bridges/` provide CLI entrypoints for context-compaction callers; current status is documented inside the per-folder README.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/tests/code-graph-query-handler.vitest.ts:\n  Line 655:           fqName: 'handlers.index.handleSessionStart',\n\n  Line 656:           name: 'handleSessionStart',\n\n  Line 663:           fqName: 'hooks.opencode.handleSessionStart',\n\n  Line 664:           name: 'handleSessionStart',\n\n  Line 682:       subject: 'handleSessionStart',\n\n  Line 690:         subject: 'handleSessionStart',\n\n  Line 709:       fqName: `handlers.shadow.handleSessionStart${index + 1}`,\n\n  Line 710:       name: 'handleSessionStart',\n\n  Line 717:       fqName: 'hooks.opencod